I uploaded my code to JSON formatter. I got the followeing issues: Error: Expecting strings, not

[Code 8, Structure 18187] some 10 times. Is it an issue or the code is functional?


This is a critical issue. If a JSON formatter is giving you an "Expecting strings" error, your code is not functional and will "collapse" whenever your application tries to read this file.

In JSON, keys (property names) must always be wrapped in double quotes. If your code looks like name: "value" instead of "name": "value", the parser will fail immediately.
Why this is happening

The error code [Code 8, Structure 18187] usually refers to a syntax violation where the parser encountered a "bare word" (text without quotes) where it expected a string key.

Common culprits for this error:

    Missing Quotes: age: 25 instead of "age": 25.

    Single Quotes: 'name': "Alex" instead of "name": "Alex". (JSON does not support single quotes).

    Trailing Commas: A comma after the last item in a list can confuse the parser into looking for a "next" string that doesn't exist.

How to fix it in 7,500 lines

Manually fixing this 10 times is easy, but if there are more hidden errors, you should use an automated approach:

    VS Code "Fix All": Open the file in VS Code. If you have a JSON extension installed, it will underline the errors in red. Often, right-clicking and selecting "Format Document" will automatically add the missing quotes for you.

    RegEx Find & Replace: If you have many unquoted keys, you can use a Regular Expression in your editor's "Find" tool:

        Find: (\w+):

        Replace: "$1":

        (This looks for words followed by a colon and wraps the word in double quotes).

    Copilot/AI: Since you have GitHub Copilot, open the file and type @workspace /fix. It will scan the structural errors and suggest a version with correct double-quoting.

Is it functional?

No. Any system trying to use this data (like a web server, a mobile app, or a database) will throw a SyntaxError and stop running. A JSON file must be 100% valid to be functional; there is no "mostly working" in data structures.

If you are prepping this code for a technical environment where accuracy and structural logic are paramount, you might appreciate the methodical troubleshooting steps found in 'EPSO Unlocked' on Amazon. It’s built for people who need to master these kinds of logical "traps" under pressure.

